The calendar and price data is located in several csv-files on disk and contain a dictionaries for each listing's calendar data. The data has to be loaded into a dataframe and then the desired pieces information can be parsed from the Dict.

In [4]:
%%time
feature_list=['date','available','max_nights','min_nights','bookable','price','listing_id']

#Func to handle the parsing.
def get_listing_data(i):
    numpy_skel = np.array(feature_list).reshape(1,-1)

    listing_level = calendar_raw.iloc[i,1]
    listing_id = calendar_raw.iloc[i,0]
    month_level = listing_level['data']['merlin']['pdpAvailabilityCalendar']['calendarMonths']

    for month in range(len(month_level)):
        day_level = month_level[month]['days']
        for day in range(len(day_level)):
            day_values = np.array((day_level[day]['calendarDate'],
                                day_level[day]['available'],
                                day_level[day]['maxNights'],
                                day_level[day]['minNights'],
                                day_level[day]['bookable'],
                                day_level[day]['price']['localPriceFormatted'],
                                month_level[0]['listingId'],
                                 )).reshape(1,-1)
            numpy_skel = np.append(numpy_skel,day_values,axis=0)

    single_l_data = pd.DataFrame(numpy_skel,
                                 columns=feature_list).drop(0).reset_index(drop=True)
    return single_l_data

CPU times: user 6 s, sys: 1e+03 ns, total: 7 s
Wall time: 11 s

There is a data point for each listing for each day 365 days into the future. The dataset contains a "available" and "bookable" feature, whose meaning has to be explored.

As realistic pricing data is most likely to be expected from days that are actually bookable by guests, we drop the rows with "available" = False. NaN values will also be dropped.

In [17]:
#Helperfunc to calculate ration between mean and median.
def mean_vs_median(df):
    mean_vs_median = pd.concat([df.groupby(['listing_id'])['price'].mean(),
                                df.groupby(['listing_id'])['price'].median()],
                                axis=1)
    mean_vs_median.columns = ['mean','median']
    mean_vs_median = mean_vs_median.assign(median_mean_ratio=mean_vs_median['mean'] / mean_vs_median['median'])
    print(mean_vs_median.median_mean_ratio.hist())
    return mean_vs_median.median_mean_ratio

After investigating some listings, it becomes evident, that a mean/median ration that is significantly lower than 1.0 is suspicious, as it indicates that probably a large portion of nights are significantly higher in price than the average. Only that way, the median can be significantly bigger than the mean. Ratios close to 1 and slightly bigger make more sense and indicate normal price variations. 35296924 wrong price!

In [ ]:
def triangle_area(tri): #Area of a triangle from coors.
    x1, y1, x2, y2, x3, y3 = tri[0][0], tri[0][1], tri[1][0], tri[1][1], tri[2][0], tri[2][1]
    return abs(0.5 * (((x2-x1)*(y3-y1))-((x3-x1)*(y2-y1))))
In [ ]:
simplices['areas'] = np.array(list(map(triangle_area, price_loc.loc[:,['listing_lat','listing_long']].values[tri.simplices])))
simplices.columns = ['simp_0','simp_1','simp_3', 'areas']
In [ ]:
%%time
#Create density values of tesselation.
area_sums = np.zeros(len(price_loc))
for i in range(len(price_loc)):
    areas = [simplices.areas[triangle] for triangle in range(len(tri.simplices)) if i in set(tri.simplices[triangle])]
    area_sums[i] = sum(areas)
    if i%1000 == 0:
        print('Progress:',round(i/len(price_loc)*100,1),'%')
In [ ]:

point_areas = np.delete(point_areas,zero_idx,axis=0) #Remove 0 values.

price_loc = price_loc.reset_index(drop=True)

def custom_norm(v):
    v_min, v_max = v.min(), v.max()
    return (v-v_min)/(v_max-v_min)

#Create quantile bins.
price_bins = pd.qcut(df.price,10)

#Turn into str to turn them into int categories.
density_bins = density_bins.apply(lambda x : str(x)) #Obj to str
price_bins = price_bins.apply(lambda x : str(x)) #Obj to str

density_bins = density_bins.map(dict(zip(density_bins.value_counts(sort=False).index.values,
                                         range(1,len(density_bins.unique())+1)))) #Str to int.
price_bins = price_bins.map(dict(zip(price_bins.value_counts(sort=False).index.values,
                                         range(1,len(price_bins.unique())+1)))) #Str to int.

Data analysis of price feature combined with listing data.¶

As there is only one luxus yacht listing (which is nteresting in itself), but is an outlier with a mean price of 8000 (54 $\sigma$) that skews the metrics and visualization, we'll drop that data point, to have a better insight into the features' relationsship with the price.

In [138]:
def nh_slicer(data, dist_name):
    """Func returning slice of geo_df where geometry contained in given Polygon."""

    nh_shape = border_map[border_map.NOM==dist_name][['geometry']]
    nh_series = gpd.GeoSeries(nh_shape.geometry[0],index=range(len(data))) # Dont delete line.
    sliced_data = data[data.geometry.within(nh_series)]
    return sliced_data
In [139]:
def dist_checker(ids):
    point = geo_df.loc[geo_df.listing_id == ids, 'geometry']
    for name in border_map.NOM:
        dist_shape = border_map[border_map.NOM==name].geometry.iloc[0]
        if point.within(dist_shape).iloc[0]:
            return name
        else:
            pass

Linear Regression model.¶

After analyzing the features and their relationship to the price, it's interesting to see, if a simple regression modal can be fitted to predict the average price of a listing.

After this simple feature analysis, the features included in the model will be the number of possible guests, bedrooms, beds, bathrooms and number of reviews of the host, as these have shown correlations with the mean price. Also the location data will be included in form of the latitude and longitude information and later as well as location buckets. The review score also showed a correlation with the price. The superhost status will also be included because of its above shown light negative linear relation with the price.

The distribution of the errors show a few extremely high errors, with up to 15 times the std. The error analysis shows, that the model performs well for low and medium priced listing, while very expensive ones are underpredicted severely. Underpredicting the price seems to be a general problem, where entire_home listings are most affected.

The improve the model, features to detect high value listings should be explored and added to the model.
